@pdion891 @remibergsma we already have a jenkins systemvm build which takes git branch as parameter.
http://jenkins.buildacloud.org/view/parameterized/job/parameterized-sytemvm/
http://jenkins.buildacloud.org/view/parameterized/

@wido the default value is 0, which means the statistics is disabled by default.
I will remove the 300 seconds limitation if most of us agree.
the vm disk statistics has the same setting to vm network statistics.

@karuturi I think we can remove the loop only if we does not support Ubuntu 12.04 and CentOS 6.X any more.
This PR LGTM if we assume the virtio port will work at the end (I mean in 30 times try).
Because the /var/cache/cloud/cmdline exists after starting, so the loop will terminate.

@jburwell, we've adapted the client so it's not throwing the broad Exception anymore.
We're not catching any longer on the broad Exception, but rather on the subset of exceptions.
We've added the equals tests as requested.

@nvazquez Thanks for your work on the commits, they are much better now. I would say it can easily be improved even further, but given the current practice in the project, it is already good!

As @remibergsma pointed out, it would be best if you apply your changes to master. However if you want to use the functionality you added in a new minor version of an older release, then make a PR for the branch of that release, and we will help you port your changes all the way up to master. We have worked on a workflow that helps with that (https://cwiki.apache.org/confluence/display/CLOUDSTACK/Release+principles+for+Apache+CloudStack+4.6+and+up#ReleaseprinciplesforApacheCloudStack4.6andup-Whymergingforwardovercherry-pickingfrommaster?)

EDIT: and btw I think you missed one commented out line in https://github.com/apache/cloudstack/pull/935#discussion-diff-42215862R164

@rodrigo93, nice work. However, you forgot an entry in /cloud-client-ui/pom.xml.
If that “cloud-plugin-storage-allocator-random” is not needed you should remove the dependency from “cloud-client-ui” project. 

Additionally, could you squash your commits?
